<p><i><b>The Theory of the Leisure Class</b></i> is a book, first published in 1899, by the Norwegian-American <a href="/wiki/Economist" title="Economist">economist</a> <a href="/wiki/Thorstein_Veblen" title="Thorstein Veblen">Thorstein Veblen</a> while he was a professor at the <a href="/wiki/University_of_Chicago" title="University of Chicago">University of Chicago</a>.</p>
<p>Veblen claimed he wrote the book as a perceptive personal essay criticizing contemporary culture, rather than as an economics textbook. Critics claim this was an excuse for his failure to cite sources. Nonetheless, <i>Theory of the Leisure Class</i> is considered one of the great works of economics as well as the first detailed critique of <a href="/wiki/Consumerism" title="Consumerism">consumerism</a>.</p>
